# n8n-decanter — guide for coding agents

This is the **source of truth** for working in this repository, and it is written to
be tool-agnostic. Codex and opencode read this file natively; Claude Code reads it
through a one-line `@AGENTS.md` import in `CLAUDE.md`; other agents can be pointed at
this file directly. Keep project-specific rules here so every agent stays in sync.

This repo holds the **Code-node source** of n8n workflows *decanted* into
git-friendly form: one folder per workflow containing a read-only
`workflow.json` structure snapshot plus a `code/` subdir with one source file
per Code node. The `n8n-decanter` CLI syncs the code with the live n8n
instance over n8n's **MCP server** (`pull` / `push` — draft-first, code-only).
This document is the contract for creating and editing these files.

## The short version

- **Code lives in `code/`, never in `workflow.json`.** A node's `jsCode` is only
  a `//@file:code/<name>` placeholder — edit the file it points at.
- **Code-node source is authored HERE and synced by decanter — never edited on
  the n8n instance directly** (not in the UI, not via MCP tools, not via n8n
  skills). The git files are the single source of truth for code.
- **Workflow structure has no editable file here — it lives in n8n.**
  `workflow.json` is a read-only snapshot for review and offline tooling; you
  restructure a workflow over the guarded MCP surface (below), not by editing
  it — editing it changes nothing remotely
  and the next `pull` overwrites it. Make structure changes in the n8n editor
  or through n8n's own MCP tools (the scaffolded `n8n-instance` MCP server is
  the guarded route) — creating and renaming workflows, adding/renaming/wiring
  nodes, archiving. `pull` reconciles the local mirror afterwards.
- **Never hand-edit `.decanter.json`, and never write a `// @ts-n8n sha256:`
  marker.** These are machine-owned; touching them corrupts sync state and the
  CLI blocks it at `push`.
- **`push` writes the DRAFT and is part of finishing the work — code that only
  exists in this folder is not done. `publish` (or `push --publish`) changes
  what is actually running and needs the user's say-so.** Edit, verify offline
  with `n8n-decanter check` and `n8n-decanter node run`, then push.

The rest of this document is the full contract behind those points.

## How this differs from standard n8n editing — read this first

Your general n8n knowledge (docs, n8n MCP tools, official n8n skills, training
data) is **valid** for: node types and parameters, expression syntax,
connection semantics, the Code-node runtime, and workflow *structure* work. It
is **wrong** about how Code-node code is stored and edited here. The deviations:

1. **`jsCode` in `workflow.json` never contains code.** Its entire value is a
   placeholder: `//@file:code/<filename>`
   (e.g. `"jsCode": "//@file:code/amazon-feed.ts"`).
   Never inline JavaScript into `workflow.json`; edit the referenced file.
2. **Code node sources live in the folder's `code/` subdir**, named after the
   node in kebab-case (`Amazon Feed` → `code/amazon-feed.ts`). `.js` files are
   pushed verbatim (what you write is exactly what runs in n8n). `.ts` files
   are compiled on push; the local `.ts` is the only source of truth — n8n
   holds compiled output.
3. **Never edit a Code node's `jsCode` on the instance** — not in the n8n UI,
   not with `update_workflow` from n8n's MCP server, not by following an n8n
   skill that says to. That bypasses the repo and drifts the source of truth;
   the decanter's per-node drift guard will flag it on the next push. Edit the
   file here and `push`.
4. **`workflow.json` is a read-only snapshot.** Pull writes it; nothing pushes
   it. Structure changes (nodes, connections, parameters like a Code node's
   `mode`, settings, positions) belong in n8n — the editor or n8n's MCP tools
   (via the guarded server). The one local edit that IS meaningful:
   re-pointing a `//@file:` placeholder (e.g. `.js` → `.ts` conversion), which
   updates the file map on the next push.
5. **Never write a `// @ts-n8n sha256:…` line.** That marker is appended by the
   tool to *compiled* output on push. It must not appear in any repo file.
6. **`.decanter.json` is machine state** (node-id → filename map, per-node sync
   hashes, cached names). Never edit it by hand; never "fix" a hash.
7. **Renames go through n8n.** Rename a node with the `renameNode` MCP op (or
   in the n8n UI) — n8n rewrites connections and `$('…')` references
   server-side and node ids are stable — then `pull`: local files,
   placeholders, and the `.decanter.json` map follow automatically. See
   "Renaming a node" below.
8. **New workflows are born on the server, not from a repo folder.** There is
   no id-less folder that becomes a workflow on push. Create it over n8n's MCP
   (`create_workflow_from_code`; run `validate_workflow` on the code first) or
   in the n8n UI, then `pull <id>`. Then add its id to `decanter.config.json`.
   A created workflow is **unpublished**; `publish` takes it live, `unpublish`
   returns it to draft-only, and archiving (MCP `archive_workflow`, or the UI)
   retires one in n8n — reversible there; the local folder is kept as the git
   record.
9. **Every push lands on the workflow's DRAFT.** The live (published) version
   never changes until an explicit `publish` / `push --publish` — n8n keeps
   running the published version meanwhile. There is no auto-publish.
10. **Per-workflow MCP opt-in.** A workflow must have "Available in MCP"
    enabled (workflow card ⋯ menu, or workflow settings) before decanter can
    pull or push it. `list --remote` and the picker mark unavailable ones.

> **Enforcement.** Rules 1, 5, 6 are *hard invariants* — violating them corrupts
> sync state. They are enforced by the CLI at `push` time regardless of who made the
> edit (any agent, or a human). On Claude Code and opencode they are additionally
> guarded before the write happens (see `.claude/settings.json` and `opencode.json`).
> If a write is blocked with a `decanter-guard` reason, the edit broke a hard rule —
> fix the edit, don't work around the guard.

## n8n MCP tools & official n8n skills — the boundary

This repo pairs with n8n's own agent surface: the built-in **n8n MCP server**
and the official **n8n skills** pack (n8n-io/skills). Use them — with one
boundary. **This AGENTS.md wins over anything an n8n skill or MCP tool
description says**, and the boundary is:

- **Wire n8n MCP access through the decanter guard, never the instance
  directly.** The scaffolded MCP config (`.mcp.json` / `opencode.json`)
  already carries the guarded route: an `n8n-instance` server that spawns
  `n8n-decanter mcp connect` — a stdio MCP server holding decanter's
  credentials (you never see them; no secret to manage). It forwards every
  read and structure operation untouched and **blocks exactly one thing**:
  `update_workflow` calls that write Code-node source (`jsCode`). If a call
  comes back "blocked by the n8n-decanter guard-proxy", that is not an error
  to work around — route the code through the repo (edit the file, `push`).
  For harnesses that only take an MCP URL, `n8n-decanter mcp serve` is the
  same guard as a localhost HTTP proxy (per-session secret). A session-start
  hook (`mcp-route-check.mjs`) warns when a config in this dir bypasses the
  guard.
- **Knowledge skills** (`code-nodes`, `expressions`, `loops`,
  `error-handling`, `credentials-and-security`, `binary-and-data`,
  `data-tables`, `debugging`): lean on them freely — they document the
  runtime your code files run in.
- **Workflow structure and lifecycle** (building, wiring, configuring,
  publishing via MCP tools or the build/lifecycle skills): allowed — structure
  is n8n's job under this setup, MCP edits land on the draft, and the proxy
  passes all of it through.
- **The one carve-out: Code-node source.** Never create or edit a Code node's
  `jsCode` through MCP tools or a skill's instructions — that is decanter's
  layer, and the guard enforces it technically. Author the code as a file in
  `code/` and let `push` sync it. If a skill's recipe includes writing
  Code-node code on the instance, do every other step of the recipe and
  route the code itself through the repo: add the Code node over MCP
  **without** a `jsCode` param, `pull` (it lands as an empty `code/` file),
  write the code there, `push`.

The skills pack installs whole (no cherry-pick) and is not aware of this
repo's layout — this override plus the guard-proxy, not selective
installation, is what holds the boundary.

Not installed yet? It's a plugin, not an npm dependency — a first
`n8n-decanter init` prints these too:

- **Claude Code** — in a session: `/plugin marketplace add n8n-io/skills` then
  `/plugin install n8n-skills@n8n-io`. From a shell: `claude plugin marketplace
  add n8n-io/skills` then `claude plugin install n8n-skills@n8n-io`. Either way,
  `/reload-plugins` (or a restart) activates it.
- **Codex** (≥ 0.142.0) — `codex plugin marketplace add n8n-io/skills` then
  `codex plugin add n8n-skills@n8n-io`, then restart and approve its hooks.
- **Other agents** — `npx skills add n8n-io/skills` (skills.sh; support varies).

### Routing cue for plain-skills installs

The plugin routes every n8n task through the pack automatically (SessionStart
hook). The skills.sh route has no such hook, so **if the pack was installed as
plain skills**: when working with workflows, nodes, expressions, or the n8n MCP
tools, start by loading the `using-n8n-skills-official` meta-skill and follow
its routing into the matching capability skill before acting — then apply the
Code-node override above, which wins over anything a skill says.

## File ownership

| File | Written by | May the agent edit it? |
|---|---|---|
| `workflow.json` | pull only | Only `//@file:` placeholders (file-map re-points). Everything else is a read-only snapshot — structure changes go through n8n. |
| `code/<node>.js` | pull + you | Yes — this is live node code, verbatim. |
| `code/<node>.ts` | you only | Yes — pull never touches it. |
| `.decanter.json` | tool only | No. |
| `.decanter-auth.json` | tool only | No — MCP OAuth credentials (gitignored). |
| `.decanter-proxy.json` | tool only | No — the running guard-proxy's endpoint + session secret (gitignored). |
| `decanter.config.json` | you | Yes — add/remove workflow ids. |
| `n8n-globals.d.ts` | you | Yes — extend when node code uses a global it doesn't cover yet. |

## Reading `workflow.json` (the structure snapshot)

The snapshot exists for review diffs and the offline tooling (`check`,
`node run`, `simulate` all read it). It is pretty-printed with a stable key
order so structure changes made in n8n show up as clean diffs after a `pull`.

A node object, for orientation:

```json
{
  "id": "a1b2c3d4-…",            // stable across renames — the identity anchor
  "name": "Amazon Feed",          // unique per workflow — connections + $('…') reference it
  "type": "n8n-nodes-base.code",
  "typeVersion": 2,
  "position": [880, 300],
  "parameters": {
    "mode": "runOnceForAllItems", // or "runOnceForEachItem" — set in n8n
    "jsCode": "//@file:code/amazon-feed.ts"
  }
}
```

Connections are keyed by **node name**, not id. Expressions keep their `=`
prefix (`"={{ $json.sku }}"`). None of it is pushable from here — a stale
snapshot is refreshed by `pull` (`status` prints a hint when it lags n8n).

### Renaming a node

Rename it **in n8n** — the `renameNode` MCP op (via the guarded `n8n-instance`
server) or the n8n editor. n8n rewrites connections and `$('…')` expression
references server-side. Then `pull`: the local file is renamed, the
placeholder and `.decanter.json` map follow.

Node **ids are stable across renames** — the id-keyed `.decanter.json` map is
what keeps each local file attached to its node, whoever renames it (the n8n
UI, or any agent via MCP). The next `pull` picks a rename up the same way,
whoever made it. One thing n8n does NOT rewrite: `$('…')` refs inside local
`.ts` sources (it never sees them — it holds compiled output) — update those
by hand after the pull and `push`.

Renaming a **workflow**: `setWorkflowMetadata` over MCP, or the n8n UI. The
folder is a stable local slug and is left untouched; `pull` re-caches the
display name in `.decanter.json`.

### Adding a Code node

1. Add it **in n8n** — over MCP (`update_workflow` with an `addNode` op,
   through the guarded server) or in the editor. When adding over MCP, send
   **no `jsCode`** — the guard blocks code in MCP writes by design.
2. `pull`: the node lands as an **empty** `code/` source file, with the
   `//@file:` placeholder and `.decanter.json` entry (want TypeScript?
   Replace the pulled `.js` with a `.ts` file and re-point the placeholder).
3. Write the code in the file, then `push` — the first push seeds the node's
   source. Wire it up in n8n (wiring is structure), `pull` to refresh the
   snapshot.
4. Verify: `n8n-decanter node run <file> [fixture.json]` to execute it, then
   `n8n-decanter check` (typecheck + layout).

## Writing Code node code

The runtime contract (identical for `.js` and `.ts` — types are erased):

- Code runs as a function body, **top-level `return` required**.
  - `runOnceForAllItems`: return an array of items: `[{ json: {…} }, …]`.
    Always wrap in `{ json: … }` explicitly.
  - `runOnceForEachItem`: return a single `{ json: {…} }`.
  - Editors squiggle that top-level `return`/`await` (TS1108/TS1375/TS1378) —
    a **false positive** from the editor's own tsserver; ignore it, and never
    "fix" it by wrapping the file in a function. `n8n-decanter check` wraps
    node bodies in memory before typechecking and is authoritative.
    The bundled `decanter-ts-plugin/` suppresses exactly these three codes on
    node files (all other diagnostics stay live) once tsserver runs the
    workspace TypeScript: `npm install`, then in VS Code accept
    *Use Workspace Version* (offered via `.vscode/settings.json`'s
    `typescript.tsdk`; JetBrains uses the project TypeScript by default).
- **Available globals: `n8n-globals.d.ts` is the authoritative list.** Open it
  to see every global in scope with its exact signature (`$input`, `$('Node
  Name')`, `$json`, `$binary`, the Luxon `DateTime`/`$now`/`$today`, `$workflow`,
  `$execution`, `$getWorkflowStaticData`, …). If node code needs a global that
  file doesn't declare yet, add it there.
- **Imports**: `.js` nodes — none at all (they run verbatim; assume the
  instance allows no external or built-in modules). `.ts` nodes — imports
  from inside this repo (`shared/`, relative paths) and from npm packages
  listed in `decanter.config.json`'s `"bundleDependencies"` are **bundled
  into the compiled node on push** (self-contained output, works on any
  instance incl. n8n Cloud). Rules: imports at the **top of the file** only;
  relative paths must stay inside this repo; unlisted npm packages and Node
  builtins (`node:*`, `fs`, `crypto`, …) are compile errors. Never
  `require()`.
- `console.log` is available for debugging (visible in the execution view).
- `$('Node Name')` takes the node's **name** — n8n rewrites these refs
  server-side when a node is renamed over MCP or in the UI (in `.ts` sources,
  update them by hand after the pull — n8n never sees `.ts`).

### `.js` nodes (default — lossless)

What you write is byte-for-byte what runs and what round-trips back on pull.
Type-safety via JSDoc:

```js
// @ts-check

/** @typedef {{ sku: string, qty: number }} StockLine */

/** @type {StockLine[]} */
const lines = [];
for (const item of $input.all()) {
  // …
}
return lines.map((l) => ({ json: l }));
```

- First line is `// @ts-check`.
- Prefer `@typedef` for shapes, inline casts `/** @type {Foo} */ (x)` where
  narrowing is needed. `@template`, `@satisfies` are available.
- Comments are fine and encouraged — they survive into n8n and document the
  node in place.

### `.ts` nodes (one-way)

Choose `.ts` when the type surface is heavy (large interfaces, generics,
discriminated unions). Costs, so you can weigh them:

- esbuild compiles on push: **comments are stripped** and **line numbers shift**
  — n8n error line numbers won't match the source, and the node code in the
  n8n UI is undocumented output. Documentation belongs in the `.ts`.
- Instance-side edits can't be merged back automatically — `pull` warns and
  `status --diff` shows what changed remotely; port it into the `.ts` by hand
  (the next push overwrites the remote edit).

Rules: full TS is fine (interfaces, type aliases, enums, generics); still
ends in a top-level `return`. Never commit compiled output; never add the
marker line.

**Shared code (`shared/`)**: put helpers and types used by several nodes in
`shared/*.ts` and import them from `.ts` nodes — types *and* functions:

```ts
import { total, type OrderLine } from "../../shared/money";

const lines: OrderLine[] = $input.all().map((i) => i.json as OrderLine);
return [{ json: { total: total(lines) } }];
```

Push inlines the imported code into the compiled node (each importing node
carries its own copy — keep helpers small). Editing a shared file makes every
importing node show up as "push pending" in `status`; push to propagate.
Small npm libraries work the same way once installed here (`npm i zod`) and
opted in via `"bundleDependencies": ["zod"]` in `decanter.config.json` —
pure-JS packages only (no native addons, no builtins). `.js` nodes cannot
import; give them JSDoc `@typedef`s or convert to `.ts`.

### Switching a node `.js` → `.ts` (or back)

1. Rename the file, convert JSDoc ↔ annotations.
2. Update the `//@file:` placeholder in `workflow.json` (the one meaningful
   local edit there — it re-points the file map).
3. `n8n-decanter check` to verify the layout, then **`n8n-decanter push`** —
   the push is what registers the conversion: it rewrites `.decanter.json`'s
   file map and sends the compiled code to n8n. Direction of sync changes
   accordingly (`.ts` = one-way).

**Stopping after step 2 or 3's `check` leaves the conversion local**: n8n still
runs the old code and `.decanter.json` still names the file you deleted. `check`
warns about exactly this (it is a pending sync, not an error) — heed the warning
rather than reading the green typecheck line as done.

## Verification

Two offline tools, always available (no credentials, no network, no live n8n):

- **`n8n-decanter check`** — runs the layout-compliance guard *and* the
  typecheck (the same wrapper that maps top-level-`return` node bodies back to
  real line numbers). Run it after editing any code file or `n8n-globals.d.ts`;
  treat a failure as a blocker. `npm run typecheck` is an alias for it.
  **A green `check` is not a finished task.** It is offline by definition, so it
  proves the files are well-formed — never that n8n is running them. Its success
  line says so: `OK (local layout — status compares with n8n)`. Editing and then
  stopping here is the single most common way to leave work unfinished: the repo
  looks right and the instance is unchanged. Finish with `status` (compare) and
  `push` (make it real).
- **`n8n-decanter node run <file> [fixture.json]`** — actually executes a node's body
  against a faked n8n context (`$input`, `$json`, `$('Node')`, `DateTime`, …) and
  prints the items it returns. Prefer this over hand-rolling a throwaway test
  script.
  - The optional fixture JSON supplies the context; every field is optional:

    ```json
    {
      "input":  [{ "json": { "sku": "A1" } }],
      "nodes":  { "Fetch Products": [{ "json": { "id": 1 } }] },
      "env":    { "REGION": "eu" },
      "staticData": { "global": { "cursor": 42 } }
    }
    ```

    `input` feeds `$input`/`$json`; `nodes` backs `$('Node Name')`; without a
    fixture the input defaults to a single empty item. `env` backs `$env`,
    which is **empty by default** (like n8n's scoped `$env`) — set it here, or
    pass `--allow-env` to inherit the process environment (may include
    `N8N_API_KEY`; never `run --allow-env` an untrusted node).
    `$getWorkflowStaticData` is seeded from `workflow.json`'s `staticData`
    (`global` and this node's `node:` slice); a fixture `staticData` replaces
    the matching slice (`"node"` = the node being run). Mutations are visible
    during the run but never persisted — `run` is offline.
  - Run mode (`runOnceForAllItems` / `runOnceForEachItem`) is read from the node
    in `workflow.json`, so each-item nodes are looped once per input item.
- JSON validity of `workflow.json` after every structural edit.

## Real execution data (`executions/` — temporary, gitignored)

When you need to see what data actually flows through a workflow — to write an
accurate `node run` fixture, or to debug a node against real payloads — fetch
recent executions from the instance instead of guessing shapes:

```sh
n8n-decanter executions "<workflow>"                    # 5 most recent, full run data
n8n-decanter executions "<workflow>" --status=error --limit=3
n8n-decanter executions 4711                            # one execution by its id
```

Each execution lands as `workflows/<folder>/executions/<execId>.json`. The items
a node produced are under
`data.resultData.runData["<Node Name>"][0].data.main[0][]` — each entry's
`.json` is one item, exactly what `$('<Node Name>')` (and the downstream node's
`$input`) sees at runtime. Copy real item shapes from here into `node run` fixtures.

Rules:

- **Temporary working data, never committed.** The tool writes the dir
  self-ignoring (`executions/.gitignore` containing `*`) because run data can
  hold credentials and PII — never weaken that, and never copy secrets from it
  into code or fixtures.
- **Clean up when the task that needed it is done:**
  `n8n-decanter executions clean` (offline; removes every `executions/` dir,
  or pass a workflow ref to scope it).
- **Convenience, not ground truth.** Executions run the *published* workflow
  version (n8n 2.x), which may be older than the local draft, and payloads
  change over time — re-fetch rather than trusting stale files.
- These fetches use the n8n **public API key** (`N8N_API_KEY`) — the one
  surface MCP doesn't cover. Without a key configured the verb says so.

## Runtime checks: `test` (instance) and `simulate` (offline)

Two pinned-run checks share the capture/scenario sources; **recommend `test`
first** — it runs on the instance's exact engine (community nodes included)
with no Docker. Reach for `simulate` when the run must be offline: pre-push
verification of uncommitted local code, CI without an instance,
`--network-none` isolation, engine-version rehearsal. Both diff node output
against the capture and exit 1 on divergence.

- `n8n-decanter test <workflow>` — pinned run **on the instance** (MCP;
  draft only, the live version is never touched). Non-interactive runs never
  mutate: they test the draft as-is and say so when your local edits aren't
  pushed yet — `push` first to test local code.
- `n8n-decanter simulate <workflow>` — the same idea through a **local**
  n8n engine (Docker), fully offline.
- `n8n-decanter preflight <workflow> [--json]` — **the one gate to run before
  `push`/`publish`.** It runs the whole ladder — static (`check`) + instance
  reads (`status`, execution `history`) + a pinned `test` run (`--full` adds
  `simulate`) — **read-only** and scores it into one verdict (`ready` /
  `caution` / `not ready`, exit 0/1). Read `--json` for stable check ids +
  per-check remediation; `--require=test` fails the gate unless a runtime check
  actually ran (the teeth for "must have coverage"). It **never mutates** (no
  push/publish/restore), so run it freely. The loop:
  **`… edit → check → preflight → push`**.

## Scenarios (`scenarios/` — committed pin-data sets)

A **scenario** is a named, committed input set for a workflow —
`scenarios/<slug>.json`, captured from a real run or scaffolded from the
workflow's schemas — that `test`/`simulate` replay and diff against. Both verbs
pin network nodes to it; a **gap** is a network node the replay reaches that has
**no data** (added or reparametrized since the capture). They hard-error on a
gap rather than run half-real — and filling it is a task you, the agent, are
well-suited to complete. **The CLI never calls an LLM or invents values; you
author the data locally and it is reviewed in the diff.**

The loop:

```sh
n8n-decanter simulate "<workflow>" --execution <id>                 # ✗ gap: <Node> has no data
n8n-decanter scenario create "<workflow>" "<slug>" --execution <id> # writes a committed, fillable scenario
#   → edit workflows/<folder>/scenarios/<slug>.json  (see below)
n8n-decanter scenario check "<workflow>" <slug>                     # validate offline (fast, no Docker)
n8n-decanter simulate "<workflow>" --scenario <slug>               # replay the filled scenario
```

Add `--scaffold` to `scenario create` to annotate each gap with its **output
schema** (from n8n's read-only `prepare_test_pin_data`) — a `--scaffold` with no
`--execution` builds a from-scratch set where *every* pinnable node is a fill
entry. Provenance is tracked per node: `capture` (real, diff-asserted),
`authored` (hand-filled), `scaffolded` (schema-guided). A run on a scenario with
any non-`capture` node is reported as **synthetic pins — proves executability,
not output correctness** (no per-node diff asserted).

`scenario create` copies the capture into `scenarios/<slug>.json` (a **named
scenario** — `happy-path`, `empty-cart`, …; the slug defaults to the execution
id) and adds a `_decanterScenario` block listing each gap node with its
**type**, **parameters**, an **`inputSample`** (the items feeding it), and —
with `--scaffold` — an **`expectedSchema`**. For each node in `fill`, add its
output under `data.resultData.runData`:

```jsonc
"data": { "resultData": { "runData": {
  // …existing captured nodes stay untouched…
  "<Node Name>": [                    // one entry per run (a normal node runs once)
    { "data": { "main": [             // outputs; index 0 is the node's main output
      [                               // items array for that output
        { "json": { /* the realistic output this node would emit */ } }
      ]
    ] } }
  ]
} } }
```

How to author good data:

- **Use the context.** Read the node's `type`/`parameters`, `inputSample`, and
  (if scaffolded) `expectedSchema` in the `_decanterScenario.fill` entry, and
  infer a realistic output. An HTTP GET to a CRM returns a record; a DB query
  returns rows; a Slack post returns a message-sent ack. One item in, one
  enriched item out is the common case.
- **Match the input's `pairedItem` when downstream nodes link items** (e.g.
  `$('<Node>').itemMatching(...)`): give each output item `"pairedItem": { "item": <inputIndex> }`.
- **Keep the `fill` list as-is.** It records which nodes are synthetic (not
  captured) — the provenance signal — and is what `scenario check` validates.
  Don't delete it.
- **Validate offline with `scenario check <slug>`** — a fast, node-named
  structural check that needs no Docker; run it in your fill→check→fix loop. It
  fails if an item isn't `{ "json": … }` or a `fill` node is still empty.
  `simulate --scenario` runs the same check on load. There is no official n8n
  JSON Schema — this is the decanter's own check of the exact shape it replays.
- **Committed, so review for PII.** Unlike `executions/`, `scenarios/` is tracked
  in git (reproducible replays). The data you author is synthetic, but a copied
  capture around it can hold real payloads — don't commit secrets.

## Data tables (`data-tables/` — temporary, gitignored)

When a workflow reads or writes an n8n **data table** (the built-in
project-scoped tables, n8n ≥ 2.x) and you need to see what's actually in it —
its columns or its rows — fetch it instead of guessing:

```sh
n8n-decanter data-tables                                # every table: schema + rows
n8n-decanter data-tables "Orders"                       # one table by name (or id)
n8n-decanter data-tables "Orders" --filter '{"type":"and","filters":[{"columnName":"status","condition":"eq","value":"active"}]}'
n8n-decanter data-tables "Orders" --search foo --sort total:desc --limit 50 --all
```

Data tables are **project-scoped, not owned by a workflow**, so they land in a
single **top-level `data-tables/` dir** (next to `decanter.config.json`), not
under a workflow folder. Each table becomes
`data-tables/<table-slug>/{meta,columns,rows}.json` — `columns.json` is the
schema, `rows.json` the (possibly filtered) rows, and `meta.json` records the id,
name, and the applied filter/search/sort/limit + row count, so a filtered
`rows.json` is never mistaken for the whole table.

Rules:

- **Read-only.** The CLI only ever *reads* data tables — it never creates,
  updates, or deletes a table, column, or row. (n8n's MCP tools cannot read
  rows at all — this verb rides the public API key, which is why it needs
  `N8N_API_KEY`.)
- **Temporary working data, never committed.** The dir is written self-ignoring
  (`data-tables/.gitignore` containing `*`) because tables can hold PII — never
  weaken that, and never copy secrets from it into code or fixtures.
- **Pull a slice, not the whole table.** For large tables use `--filter` (a JSON
  string of conditions, passed straight to the API), `--search` (free text),
  and `--sort` (`col:asc|desc`) to narrow rows server-side; `--limit` caps a page
  (default 100, max 250) and `--all` follows the cursor to exhaust the result.
- **Clean up when done:** `n8n-decanter data-tables clean` (offline; removes the
  whole `data-tables/` dir).
- **Config-gated.** Available when `"dataTables"` is on in `decanter.config.json`
  (its default); if it's `false` the fetch refuses (`clean` still works).

## Commands — who runs what

- **Offline, safe — run freely:** `n8n-decanter check` (or `npm run typecheck`),
  `n8n-decanter node run <file> [fixture]`,
  `n8n-decanter scenario create <workflow>` / `scenario check <workflow>` (committed pin-data sets),
  `n8n-decanter executions clean`, `n8n-decanter data-tables clean`. These never
  touch the network.
- **Reads remote, no writes:** `n8n-decanter status` (`--diff` shows the line
  diffs; exits 1 on code conflict/remote code drift), `n8n-decanter list
  --remote` (marks workflows not yet available in MCP), `n8n-decanter
  executions <workflow>` (fetches execution data, read-only), and `n8n-decanter
  data-tables [table…]` (fetches data-table schema + rows, read-only) — safe to
  run, but they do contact the instance.
- **Syncs code with the instance — part of doing the work:** `n8n-decanter
  pull` / `push` / `watch`. **A push lands on the DRAFT — it never changes what
  is running.** So when the user's request only makes sense with the code in
  n8n ("build me an hourly job…", "fix the normalise step"), pushing is how you
  finish it: leaving the code in this folder means the workflow still runs the
  old version, or nothing at all. Verify offline first (`check` + `node run`),
  then push, then say what you pushed. Two cases still call for a word first:
  the workflow is **published/active** (a stale draft can be published by
  someone else), or a **teammate is editing it** (n8n holds a single-writer
  lock and the push will fail with a lock error anyway).
- **Changes what is LIVE — only when the user explicitly asks:** `publish`
  takes the draft live, `unpublish` returns it to draft-only, `push --publish`
  combines push and go-live. This is the deliberate step; never fold it into
  "finishing the work" on your own initiative.
- **Structure and lifecycle acts** (creating/renaming workflows, adding/
  renaming/wiring nodes, archiving) go through **n8n's MCP tools** via the
  guarded `n8n-instance` server. Building the structure a request describes is
  part of the work, like a push; **renaming or archiving something that already
  exists is not** — those change what the user sees and finds, so ask first.
  **Archiving is outward-facing**
  (the workflow leaves the active list; a published one goes offline;
  reversible only in the n8n UI) — never without an explicit instruction
  naming that workflow. After any structure act the **live mirror** refreshes
  the local `workflow.json` snapshot for you in the background (no manual
  `pull` needed); run `pull` yourself only if you want it immediately or the
  mirror is disabled (`"liveMirror": false`).
- **Backups** — `n8n-decanter backup create <workflow>` captures a versioned,
  redeployable full export into a committed `backups/` folder (needs
  `N8N_API_KEY`); the file carries credential refs + any embedded secrets, so
  it is **not** auto-committed — review before `git add`. `backup restore` is
  **outward-facing** (it deploys a *new* workflow onto the instance) — only on
  an explicit instruction. `backup list` is offline.
- Never use `--force` on push without the user's explicit instruction — it
  overrides the per-node drift guard that protects code edits made on the
  instance.
- **Credentials:** MCP (OAuth via `init`, or `N8N_MCP_TOKEN`) powers the sync,
  structure, and lifecycle verbs; the optional public API key (`N8N_API_KEY`)
  powers `executions`, `data-tables`, and `backup`.
